snippet.textDisplay: It always surprises me how few people are aware of the National Reconnaissance Office. If you want an idea of how much money they have: Hubble's optical system is essentially a clone of one of their KH-11 series spy satellites, with the design gifted to NASA to save them money, as they were basically in serial production at the time; Senator Kit Bond disclosed that each of these spy satellites cost more than a Nimitz-class aircraft carrier; the NRO has launched 16 of them into space (*sixteen Hubble Space Telescopes*); the NRO considers them obsolete and has replaced them with a new generation of spy satellite, which has been deemed obsolete as well and that replacement generation has been replaced; and Hubble class telescopes are considered so worthless by the NRO at this point that they straight-up gifted two examples to NASA in 2012, free of charge, one of which is due to become the Wide Field Infrared Survey Telescope.

The Galaxy Tab S6... news sites and whatnot have been comparing it to iPad Pro, but it's really just a mild progression on the line that has much more in common to it's predecessors than an iPad Pro.
I recommend not getting news from Apple fanboy sources (yes, like Gizmodo), whoever the editor is. Avoid gadget news from there, they will compare even a newborn baby to an Apple product because the place is filled with Apple fanboy idiots who don't know the first thing on what they are talking about. Or, at the very least know that you have to take the articles they put out with a grain of salt, which is what I personally do.



If you guys wanna check it for yourselves, just read some of their reviews. New camera? Oh, let's compare it with iPhone photos. New laptop? Let's extoll the wonders of the Macbook Pro. New tablet? From ultra cheap for kids tablets all the way up to flagships and Chromebooks, let's always compare it to iPads and whatnot. It's what you get when you hire a bunch of kids who have been inside the walled garden all their lives. They know nothing about tech outside comparing it to Apple products.
And no, I'm not an Apple hater. I'm a hater of poor journalism, and biased reviews.

Holy crap man, is it this fucking HARD for entire intelligence services and government sectors with millions or billions of budget to hire ONE FRIGGIN GUY to read and learn juuust a teensy bit about encryption before they spout the fucking stupid crap they feel like doing every now and then? Is it? Like, how these people are not out of their jobs?
